d structures that produce inequalities while blaming unemployment and other social ills on the so-called laziness of particular class, racial, and ethnic groups. Jeske offers evidence of the laziness myth's harsh consequences, as well as insights into how to challenge it with other South African narratives of a good life. In contexts as diverse as rapping in a library, manufacturing leather shoes, weed-whacking neighbors' yards, negotiating marriage plans, and sharing water taps, the people described in this book will stimulate discussion on creative possibilities for seeking the good life in and out of employment, in South Africa and elsewhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlack peoplexEmploymentzSouth Africa. 0aHappinesszSouth Africa. 0aLazinesszSouth Africa. 0aQuality of lifezSouth Africa. 0aUnemployedzSouth AfricaxAttitudes. 0aUnemploymentxSocial aspectszSouth Africa. 0aWell-beingzSouth Africa. 0aWork ethiczSouth Africa. 0aWorkxPsychological aspects. 4aAnthropology. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  athe good life, causes of unemployment, racism in the workplace, unemployment in south africa, neoliberal entrepreneurial narrative.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501752537?locatt=mode:le